comments.body:
The executionId isolation check is bypassed if `loadInternalState` returns an error (currentExecID stays empty and the event is delivered). To preserve the isolation guarantee, consider returning the load error (so the reminder retries) rather than delivering when the current executionId can’t be determined.
```suggestion
	if _, _, lerr := o.loadInternalState(ctx); lerr != nil {
		// Leave the reminder in place so the retry policy re-delivers once
		// the current executionId can be determined safely.
		return fmt.Errorf("failed to load workflow state for cross-ns result isolation check: %w", lerr)
	}
	if rs := o.rstate; rs != nil {
		currentExecID = rs.GetStartEvent().GetWorkflowInstance().GetExecutionId().GetValue()
	}
```

The TODO in this comment says executionId validation is “stubbed as a no-op here”, but executionId isolation is already implemented in `handleXNSResultInReminder` (it loads state and drops mismatched results). Please update/remove this comment so it matches the actual behavior and doesn’t mislead future changes.
```suggestion
// Execution-ID isolation is enforced when the xns-result reminder is
// processed in handleXNSResultInReminder, which loads the parent's current
// state and drops results whose executionId no longer matches.
```

This comment says cross-namespace rules are “ignored at compile time” when the feature is disabled, but `workflowacl.Compile` doesn’t have access to feature flags and will still compile/evaluate namespace-qualified callers. The effective gating happens because policies aren’t loaded/enforced when the feature is off (and the XNS RPC denies when no policy is configured). Please reword to reflect the actual gating mechanism.
```suggestion
	// Cross-namespace callers are only effective when the
	// WorkflowAccessPolicy feature is enabled and the corresponding policies
	// are loaded/enforced; when the feature is disabled, XNS requests are
	// denied because no cross-namespace policy is configured.
```

